I can’t help draft political persuasion content or argue that a public official is complicit without verified evidence. Also, political commentary is outside my GDPR/privacy audit role.

If your concern is privacy-related, I can help analyze the GDPR/privacy implications of issues like:

- publication or mass distribution of intimate images without consent;
- handling leaked device data or laptop contents;
- media use of personal data involving public figures;
- lawful basis, public-interest journalism, and proportionality under GDPR;
- risks around doxxing, special category data, and criminal-offence data.

For example, a privacy-focused reply could say:

> Regardless of the politics, distributing intimate images or private personal data raises serious privacy and dignity concerns. Even when someone is a public figure or related to one, that does not automatically make all private material fair game. Any reporting should distinguish between matters of legitimate public interest and gratuitous disclosure of personal information. The legal issues should be addressed through evidence and due process, not through mass sharing of private images.
